[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] The convex programs easiest to solve are the *unconstrained* problems, or the problems with only equality constraints.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] As the equality constraints are all linear, they can be eliminated with linear algebra and integrated into the objective, thus converting an equality-constrained problem into an unconstrained one.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] In the class of unconstrained (or equality-constrained) problems, the simplest ones are those in which the objective is quadratic.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] For these problems, the KKT conditions (which are necessary for optimality) are all linear, so they can be solved analytically.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] For unconstrained (or equality-constrained) problems with a general convex objective that is twice-differentiable, Newton's method can be used.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] It can be seen as reducing a general unconstrained convex problem, to a sequence of quadratic problems.Newton's method can be combined with line search for an appropriate step size, and it can be mathematically proven to converge quickly.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] Other efficient algorithms for unconstrained minimization are gradient descent (a special case of steepest descent).
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] The more challenging problems are those with inequality constraints.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] A common way to solve them is to reduce them to unconstrained problems by adding a barrier function, enforcing the inequality constraints, to the objective function.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] Such methods are called interior point methods.They have to be initialized by finding a feasible interior point using by so-called *phase I* methods, which either find a feasible point or show that none exist.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] Phase I methods generally consist of reducing the search in question to a simpler convex optimization problem.
