[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] There is a large software ecosystem for convex optimization.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] This ecosystem has two main categories: *solvers* on the one hand and *modeling tools* (or *interfaces*) on the other hand.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] Solvers implement the algorithms themselves and are usually written in C.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] They require users to specify optimization problems in very specific formats which may not be natural from a modeling perspective.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] Modeling tools are separate pieces of software that let the user specify an optimization in higher-level syntax.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] They manage all transformations to and from the user's high-level model and the solver's input/output format.
[src:ellipsoid-method/convex-optimization] The first shows modelling tools (such as CVXPY and JuMP.jl) and the second shows solvers (such as SCS and MOSEK).
