[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] In mathematical optimization, the **cutting-plane method** is any of a variety of optimization methods that iteratively refine a feasible set or objective function by means of linear inequalities, termed *cuts*.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Such procedures are commonly used to find integer solutions to mixed integer linear programming (MILP) problems, as well as to solve general, not necessarily differentiable convex optimization problems.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] The use of cutting planes to solve MILP was introduced by Ralph E.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods for MILP work by solving a non-integer linear program, the linear relaxation of the given integer program.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] The theory of Linear Programming dictates that under mild assumptions (if the linear program has an optimal solution, and if the feasible region does not contain a line), one can always find an extreme point or a corner point that is optimal.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] The obtained optimum is tested for being an integer solution.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] If it is not, there is guaranteed to exist a linear inequality that *separates* the optimum from the convex hull of the true feasible set.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Finding such an inequality is the *separation problem*, and such an inequality is a *cut*.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] A cut can be added to the relaxed linear program.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Then, the current non-integer solution is no longer feasible to the relaxation.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] This process is repeated until an optimal integer solution is found.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Cutting-plane methods for general convex continuous optimization and variants are known under various names: Kelley's method, Kelley–Cheney–Goldstein method, and bundle methods.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] They are popularly used for non-differentiable convex minimization, where a convex objective function and its subgradient can be evaluated efficiently but usual gradient methods for differentiable optimization can not be used.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] This situation is most typical for the concave maximization of Lagrangian dual functions.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Another common situation is the application of the Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition to a structured optimization problem in which formulations with an exponential number of variables are obtained.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Generating these variables on demand by means of delayed column generation is identical to performing a cutting plane on the respective dual problem.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Cutting planes were proposed by Ralph Gomory in the 1950s as a method for solving integer programming and mixed-integer programming problems.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] However, most experts, including Gomory himself, considered them to be impractical due to numerical instability, as well as ineffective because many rounds of cuts were needed to make progress towards the solution.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Things turned around when in the mid-1990s Gérard Cornuéjols and co-workers showed them to be very effective in combination with branch-and-bound (called branch-and-cut) and ways to overcome numerical instabilities.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Nowadays, all commercial MILP solvers use Gomory cuts in one way or another.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Gomory cuts are very efficiently generated from a simplex tableau, whereas many other types of cuts are either expensive or even NP-hard to separate.
[src:ellipsoid-method/cutting-plane-method] Among other general cuts for MILP, most notably lift-and-project dominates Gomory cuts.
