[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] Intuitively, it means that the number of operations required for each additional digit of accuracy is polynomial in Size(*p*).
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoid method requires at most $2(n-1)n\cdot \ln \left({\frac {V(p)}{\epsilon }}\right)$ steps, and each step requires Poly(Size(p)) arithmetic operations.
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoid method is used on low-dimensional problems, such as planar location problems, where it is numerically stable.
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] Nemirovsky and BenTal say that it is efficient if the number of variables is at most 20-30; this is so even if there are thousands of constraints, as the number of iterations does not depend on the number of constraints.
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] However, in problems with many variables, the ellipsoid method is very inefficient, as the number of iterations grows as O(*n*2).
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] Even on "small"-sized problems, it suffers from numerical instability and poor performance in practice .
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoid method is an important theoretical technique in combinatorial optimization.
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] In computational complexity theory, the ellipsoid algorithm is attractive because its complexity depends on the number of columns and the digital size of the coefficients, but not on the number of rows.
[src:ellipsoid-method/ellipsoid-method] The ellipsoid method can be used to show that many algorithmic problems on convex sets are polynomial-time equivalent.
